# Default: treat as text, normalize line endings to LF on commit.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Force text for code and data formats
*.md         text eol=lf
*.html       text eol=lf
*.css        text eol=lf
*.js         text eol=lf
*.json       text eol=lf
*.csv        text eol=lf
*.xml        text eol=lf
*.tei        text eol=lf
*.yaml       text eol=lf
*.yml        text eol=lf
*.cff        text eol=lf

# Mark binary assets so Git doesn't try to diff them.
*.png        binary
*.jpg        binary
*.jpeg       binary
*.gif        binary
*.webp       binary
*.tif        binary
*.tiff       binary
*.pdf        binary
*.zip        binary

# --- Git LFS — INTENTIONALLY DISABLED for this repository ------------------
#
# Earlier drafts of this file routed the 22 MB index.html, the multi-MB
# OpenAtlas seed JSON files, and the Charles V manuscript PNGs through
# Git LFS.  That is the WRONG choice for a project that serves itself via
# GitHub Pages: every reviewer page load streams the LFS objects and
# consumes the repository's free monthly LFS bandwidth quota (1 GB/month
# on the free tier).  At ~22 MB per page load the quota burns out after
# roughly 45 visits — far less than a single round of Speculum review
# generates between reviewers, editorial staff, search engines, and the
# author's own debugging.
#
# Plain Git storage works correctly with GitHub Pages: the files are
# served as ordinary HTTP, with no per-month bandwidth ceiling beyond
# the standard Pages quota (100 GB/month, which is generous).  The
# trade-off is a slower initial `git clone` for collaborators; for a
# review-deposited static site that trade-off is the right one.
#
# Re-introduce LFS only if (a) the project moves OFF GitHub Pages, or
# (b) GitHub raises the LFS bandwidth allowance, or (c) the repository
# is split so that the served bundle lives separately from the heavy
# binary archives that genuinely need LFS.
